Motivation and Background

Give an overview of the project, motivation, background and goals.

In recent years, live streaming has emerged globally due to the internet, with many people in the world today either consuming such content, or are creating it themselves, through various live streaming platforms. Two of these platforms, Twitch and Youtube, have grown to become large content hubs, covering millions of hours of content and many viewers. Twitch, especially, is a content hub focused on the live streaming of games. In this project, I aim to analyze the popularity of these platforms, the changing viewership of live streaming content creators on these platforms (also called 'live streamers'), as well as the content of those streams.

Summary of Research Questions & Results

Repeat your research questions in a numbered list. After each research question, clearly state the answer/conclusion you determined. Do not give details or justifications yet just the answer
  1. How has the popularity of these platforms changed over time?
  • The popularity of Youtube is slightly decreasing, while Twitch's popularity has increased and has been more or less stable over the past year.
  1. How has the distribution of views changed over time?
  • The distribution for the number of views per stream on Youtube is becoming more clustered, with its mode having increased from past years, while the views gained per month for top streamers has its distribution gradually spreading, and the mode of the views gained consistently increasing.
  1. How has the proportion of gaming content changed for each site?
  • Twitch has a large percentage of streams being games. However, Youtube's percentage is low and this percentage is on a decreasing trend for both of these platforms, although the effect is not very pronounced on Twitch.
  1. What are the top few games on each platform, and how has their stream time changed?
  • The most streamed game on Youtube would be League of Legends, and Fortnite for Twitch. However, the stream time for games on Youtube is on a decreasing trend, with a sharp spike in July 2022, while it is on a slight increasing trend for Twitch with some stagnation in the past year.
  1. What is the relationship between the stream time and the number of followers gained for Twitch streamers?
  • There is no correlation between the stream time and the followers gained.

Dataset

Numbered list of dataset (with downloadable links) and a brief but clear description of each dataset used. Draw reference to the numbering when describing methodology (data cleaning and analysis).

  1. https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=all&q=%2Fm%2F09jcvs,%2Fm%2F0hgpf7h This data contains the amount of searches for Youtube and Twitch.

  2. https://sullygnome.com/games/watched This data contains the games streamed on Twitch. To obtain my data, this data is filtered and analysed by month, where corresponing sets of 100 entries are downloaded.

  3. https://sullygnome.com/channels/watched This data contains the streamers on Twitch. The data obtaining process is the same as above, where entries are repeatedly downloaded, until January 2016 where the data ends. The data only shows for the 1st 5100 entries.

  4. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/search/list This is just the documentation for querying the livestreams from youtube via its api.

  5. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/videos/list To get further information on the Youtube video, the results from the function above has to be cleaned and fed into this function, which allows us to view the genres of the video. (To get the game name, it can simply be webscraped off of youtube using the videoid already obtained.)

  6. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/videoCategories/list To get further information on the video categories, we can query through this, to get data on how the category id corresponds to each category.

#clean up the json on the allytvids

def foo(row): #parses the json in that row using this library
    try:
        ans = ast.literal_eval(row)
    except ValueError:
        return '{}'
    return ans
c=allytvids.id.apply(foo) #apply this on the row 'id'
new = pd.DataFrame(c.tolist()) #data from above into a dataframe
allytvids.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)
allytvids = pd.concat([allytvids, new], axis=1) #merge the dataframe to the original allytvids
allytvids = allytvids.drop('id', axis=1) #delete the id column, since all the data is already parsed and merged

#similar for below, but applied on the column 'snippet'
c=allytvids.snippet.apply(foo)
new = pd.DataFrame(c.tolist())
allytvids = pd.concat([allytvids, new], axis=1)

#some data cleaning of the jsons is required in some columns
cols = ['snippet', 'statistics','topicDetails', 'liveStreamingDetails'] #these are the columns to parse the json

#we shall reuse the json parsing function coded earlier for this use, but modify a bit due to the topicdetails column being blank

def foo(row): #parses the json in that row using this library
    try:
        ans = ast.literal_eval(row)
    except ValueError:
        return {'topicCategories':['']}
    return ans

for s in cols:
    #in fact, the code is the same as above but looped over the columns
    c=df[s].apply(foo)
    new = pd.DataFrame(c.tolist())
    df = pd.concat([df, new], axis=1)
    df = df.drop(s, axis=1)


#drop columns with no useful data

df = df.drop(['kind_x', 'etag_x', 'kind_y', 'etag_y', 'thumbnails', 'liveBroadcastContent', 'defaultLanguage',
             'localized', 'publishTime', 'favoriteCount'], axis=1)
df = df.loc[:,~df.columns.duplicated()]

#convert some cols to numeric
df[["categoryId", "viewCount", "likeCount", "commentCount"]] = df[["categoryId", "viewCount", "likeCount", "commentCount"]].apply(pd.to_numeric)

df.to_excel('final_yt_data/actual_yt_data.xlsx', index=False)
df.head()

The excel files available are split into batches of 100 per month, so merging, checking for missing data and removing duplicates will be necessary to summarise all of the data obtained in a month, and ensure that missing data in between is accounted for.

In[23]:
#merges the data obtained from sullygnome.com per month

#where the files are located
#this filename is changed for every folder for all of the months in the date range.

#this is not looped over since I wanted to individually check for missing values after downloading each month separately
extra_filepath = '/twitch_game_data/jun2021'

path = os.getcwd() + extra_filepath
#get all files in filepath
files = os.listdir(path)

#get all excel files
files_xlsx = [f for f in files if f[-4:] == 'xlsx']

#remove month_merged, if it exists, since we do not want to include data from there
try:
    files_xlsx.remove('month_merged.xlsx')
except Exception:
    pass

df = pd.DataFrame()

#read all the files
for f in files_xlsx:
    data = pd.read_excel(extra_filepath[1:] + '/' + f, 'Sheet1')
    df = pd.concat([df, data])
    
#drop duplicates if any, maybe downloaded twice
df.drop_duplicates(subset=[df.columns[0]], keep='first', inplace=True)

#sort the rows according to their ranking
df.sort_values(by=[df.columns[0]], inplace=True)

#renaming columns
c_name = list(df.iloc[-1])
c_name[0] = df.columns[0]
c_name[1] = 'Profile pic'
c_name[-1] = 'Channel2'
df.columns = c_name

#if the ranking is nan, it must be garbage data, drop it
df.dropna(subset=[df.columns[0]], inplace=True)

#check for missing data
indexes = (df.iloc[:,0].unique())
indexes.sort()
indexes = [x for x in indexes if str(x) != 'nan']
#continuous set from 1st to last index
vals = np.arange(indexes[0], indexes[-1] + 1)
#find the missing values
missing = list(set(indexes).symmetric_difference(set(vals)))

if(missing != []):
    #if the list is not empty, there is missing data, so do not convert to excel
    #the missing data can be manually downloaded
    #these show the missing pages to download
    missing = [x/100 for x in missing if x%100 == 0]
    print(missing)
    #the missing data downloaded have been listed with letters

else:
    #no missing data
    df.to_excel(extra_filepath[1:] + '/' + 'month_merged.xlsx',index=False)

Now we need to merge the per month streamers and games data together into separate excel files. Due to the process shown earlier, the compiled data is stored in month_merged in every folder. Each folder is named with its month and its year in that order. We must preserve the month and year data, so we shall put them as separate columns.

In[25]:
path = os.getcwd() + '/twitch_streamer_data'

list_subfolders_with_paths = [f.path for f in os.scandir(path) if f.is_dir()]
temp = []
for p in list_subfolders_with_paths:
    month = p[-7:-4]
    year = p[-4:]
    d = pd.read_excel(p+'/month_merged.xlsx')
    d.insert(loc=0, column='Date', value=year + '-' + month)
    temp.append(d)
t_streamer = pd.concat(temp)
t_streamer['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(t_streamer['Date'], format='%Y-%b')

1. How has the popularity of these platforms changed over time?

It is important for budding live streamers about to use these sites to be aware of the popularity of the site. By analysing the change in the frequency of these searches and the number of views/watch time against time, we can get an estimate on how the popularity of the sites will change in the future.

General

We can start by analysing the google trends data. These trends data are from the relative numbers of people searching for these sites, and would be a good indicator of a site's growth or decline.

In[32]:
q1all = a_trend

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.title('Relative frequency of searches against time')
plt.show()

As we can see from this graph, the relative search frequency of Youtube is many times more than that of Twitch, with a peak at around 2012. However, it appears that the site is on a decline after 2012, save for the sudden rise and fall in middle 2013 and early 2016. The data for Twitch is much too overshadowed by the Youtube data, and we will have to plot a separate graph to get insights.

In[33]:

This graph shows more detail, and shows that from Twitch's inception in 2008 to the middle of 2011, it did not gain much attention. (The data point in early 2004 is anomalous since Twitch had not been created) After the middle of 2011, the site gained massive attention, with the number of searches growing until today.

Another way of answering this question is to take into account the live stream views, since these platforms, more so for Twitch, are reliant of live stream views for their site to grow. If more people were to search for these streams and watch them, this would necessarily mean that the site is more popular.

IRL = ['Just Chatting', 'Pools, Hot Tubs and Beaches', 'ASMR', 'Talk Shows & Podcasts', 'Travel & Outdoors', 'Sports',
      'Special Events', 'Animals, Aquariums & Zoos', 'Science & Technology', 'Politics', 'Fitness & Health']
Creative = ['Music', 'Art', 'Makers & Crafting', 'Food & Drink', 'Software & Game Development', 'Beauty & Body Art']

#sorts each 'game' into a category (not everything in 'Game' is a proper game)
def classify(row):
    if row.Game in IRL:
        return 'IRL'
    if row.Game in Creative:
        return 'Creative'
    return 'Games'

Recommendations or Further Works

State any recommendations, improvements or further works.

The dataset for Twitch streamers is not complete and only has the 1st 5100 entries. To get a better understanding for Twitch streamers, a better dataset containing this data must be found.

Besides, the Youtube dataset is not complete, and querying its API returns more recent streams than those from 2015. So, the scraping for older live streams can be broken down into smaller time duration for more results.

It would also be useful to investigate how the like count and duration of live streams for Youtube are related, and more data can be obtained on the proportion of streams of games from specific streamers to investigate the correlation between streams of a certain game and the followers gained on Twitch.
